  '87e8ecd4-db62-4f66-a8fb-cc14b61c17fb',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$PHP's Type System — Strict Types, Union Types, and Where Inference Falls Short$escape$,
  $escape$PHP's type system is opt-in by default. Without `declare(strict_types=1)`, PHP silently coerces `'42'` to `42` when a function expects `int`. Add that declaration at the top of every file and PHP throws a `TypeError` instead — catching bugs that would otherwise survive to production.

PHP 8.0 added union types (`int|string`), 8.1 added intersection types (`Countable&Iterator`), and 8.2 added `true`, `false`, and `null` as standalone types. Combined with `readonly` properties (8.1) and readonly classes (8.2), you can model immutable domain objects without a third-party library.

PHP lacks generics — `array<string, User>` is a PHPStan/Psalm annotation, not enforced at runtime. The gap matters: a typed `array` parameter accepts any array regardless of element types. Tools like PHPStan at level 9 or Psalm at `errorLevel 1` fill this void statically, rejecting mismatched collection types before execution. For production codebases, running PHPStan in CI is the closest PHP gets to compile-time generic safety.$escape$,
  $escape$<?php
declare(strict_types=1);

final readonly class Money {
    public function __construct(
        public int $amount,
        public string $currency,
    ) {}
}

function add(Money $a, Money $b): Money {
    if ($a->currency !== $b->currency) {
        throw new \InvalidArgumentException('Currency mismatch');
    }
    return new Money($a->amount + $b->amount, $a->currency);
}

$total = add(new Money(100, 'USD'), new Money(50, 'USD'));
echo $total->amount; // 150$escape$,
  $escape$php$escape$,
