INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '1e5c77cf-13be-438d-9ae8-8d4efd2d09b6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$PHP Composer Lock Files — Why You Must Commit composer.lock$escape$,
  $escape$Composer resolves dependencies using two files: `composer.json` (your constraints) and `composer.lock` (the exact resolved versions). When you run `composer install`, Composer installs exactly what's in `composer.lock` — not the latest matching version. This guarantees every developer and every CI/CD deployment runs identical dependency trees.

Skipping `composer.lock` from version control is a common mistake. Without it, `composer install` silently upgrades packages to their latest allowed versions, breaking reproducibility.

For dependency auditing, run `composer audit` (available since Composer 2.4) to check all installed packages against the PHP Security Advisories Database. It exits with a non-zero code on vulnerabilities, making it CI-friendly.

Version constraints matter too: `^1.2` allows `>=1.2.0 <2.0.0`, while `~1.2` allows `>=1.2.0 <1.3.0`. Prefer `^` for libraries, but pin transitive dependencies via `composer.lock`, not by over-constraining `composer.json`. Use `composer outdated` to surface stale packages without breaking your lock file.$escape$,
  $escape$# Install exact versions from composer.lock (never resolves newer)
composer install

# Update a single package and regenerate composer.lock
composer update guzzlehttp/guzzle

# Audit all installed packages for known CVEs
composer audit

# Check for outdated packages without modifying lock file
composer outdated

# Verify lock file is in sync with composer.json
composer validate --strict$escape$,
