INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '48371e55-b478-41e1-9a18-b757e2b1b0d3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$PHP's JIT Compiler — What It Actually Does to Your Runtime$escape$,
  $escape$PHP has always been interpreted: each request parses and compiles source to opcodes, executes them, then discards everything. OPcache changed the second part — it caches compiled opcodes in shared memory, eliminating re-parsing on subsequent requests. But opcodes still run through the Zend VM interpreter on every call.

PHP 8.0 introduced a true JIT compiler (tracing and function modes) built on top of OPcache. When enabled, hot code paths are compiled to native machine code at runtime. The catch: PHP's bottleneck is almost never CPU-bound computation — it's I/O, database queries, and serialization. Benchmarks consistently show JIT yields 5–10% gains in typical web workloads, but 2–3x speedups in pure computation (math-heavy loops, image processing).

Cold start is the real cost. On the first request after a worker spawn (PHP-FPM), OPcache is cold, JIT profiling hasn't started, and class autoloading hits disk. Preloading (`opcache.preload`) solves this: PHP loads and compiles a bootstrap script at FPM startup, caching classes and functions in shared memory permanently — cold start effectively disappears for preloaded symbols.$escape$,
  $escape$# php.ini / FPM pool config
opcache.enable=1
opcache.memory_consumption=256
opcache.jit_buffer_size=128M
; tracing JIT — best for mixed workloads
opcache.jit=tracing

; Preload bootstrap (eliminates cold-start for core classes)
opcache.preload=/var/www/app/preload.php
opcache.preload_user=www-data

# preload.php
<?php
require_once __DIR__ . '/vendor/autoload.php';
// Force-load hot classes into shared memory at FPM startup
class_exists(\App\Http\Kernel::class);
class_exists(\App\Models\User::class);$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
