INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '664fbda3-1231-43fc-9f5b-b9ed25c72fe2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$PHP Memory Management — Refcounting, Cyclic GC, and WeakReferences$escape$,
  $escape$PHP uses reference counting (refcount) via the Zend Memory Manager — every zval tracks how many variables point to it. When refcount drops to zero, memory is freed immediately, no GC cycle needed. Arrays and strings use copy-on-write (COW): `$b = $a` doesn't copy heap data until mutation, cutting allocations in read-heavy paths.

The catch: circular references. If `$a->next = $b` and `$b->next = $a`, refcount never hits zero. PHP's cyclic GC (Tarjan's algorithm over a root buffer) handles these periodically. In long-running processes — CLI daemons, queue workers — call `gc_collect_cycles()` manually to reclaim cycles before they pile up. Monitor pressure with `memory_get_peak_usage(true)`.

For caches that shouldn't pin objects in memory, use `WeakReference::create($obj)`. The referent can still be collected; call `$ref->get()` and check for null before use.

Stack vs heap: PHP has no true stack allocation for objects — everything routes through ZMM's arena allocator. In PHP 8, scalar zvals (int, bool, null) are inlined into the zval struct itself, avoiding a heap round-trip entirely.$escape$,
  $escape$<?php
class Node {
    public ?Node $next = null;
    public function __destruct() { echo "freed\n"; }
}

$a = new Node();
$b = new Node();
$a->next = $b;
$b->next = $a; // cycle: destructor never fires on unset alone

unset($a, $b);
echo gc_collect_cycles() . " cycle(s) collected\n"; // 1 cycle(s) collected

// WeakReference: cache without blocking GC
$obj = new Node();
$ref = WeakReference::create($obj);
unset($obj);
var_dump($ref->get()); // NULL — already freed$escape$,
  $escape$php$escape$,
