INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'aac9cda8-430e-4eaf-a096-facc8cc167ae',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$PHP's Shared-Nothing Model — Why Horizontal Scaling Is Both Easy and Tricky$escape$,
  $escape$PHP's shared-nothing architecture means every request spawns a clean process via PHP-FPM, with zero shared memory between workers. This makes horizontal scaling straightforward: spin up more FPM pools or containers and put a load balancer (nginx, HAProxy) in front. No inter-process coordination, no distributed lock contention on application state.

The catch: OPcache is per-process. Each FPM worker warms its own opcode cache independently, so freshly forked workers take a brief latency hit until cache fills. Set `opcache.jit_buffer_size` and `pm.max_children` deliberately — over-provisioning workers exhausts memory without throughput gains.

Stateful data (sessions, rate-limit counters, queued jobs) must live externally. PHP's blocking synchronous model means a worker is fully occupied for the request lifetime. Redis for sessions (`session.save_handler = redis`), a proper queue worker (Laravel Horizon, Symfony Messenger with workers scaled independently) and sticky-session-free design are prerequisites for clean horizontal scale-out.

PHP 8.1 Fibers enable cooperative multitasking within a single worker, but they don't change the FPM process model — they're only meaningful in long-running runtimes like Swoole or ReactPHP.$escape$,
  $escape$; php-fpm pool config for horizontal scaling
[www]
pm = dynamic
pm.max_children = 50
pm.start_servers = 10
pm.min_spare_servers = 5
pm.max_spare_servers = 20
pm.max_requests = 500   ; recycle workers to prevent memory leaks

; php.ini — per-worker opcode cache
opcache.enable = 1
opcache.memory_consumption = 128
opcache.jit_buffer_size = 64M
opcache.validate_timestamps = 0   ; disable in prod, deploy triggers reset$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
